<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Title</title>
    <meta charset='utf-8'>
    <link rel='icon' type='image/svg+xml' href='static/favicon.svg'>
    <script>
      var notesEnabled =  false ;
    </script>
    <script src='static/slides.js'></script>
  </head>

  <body style='display: none'>
    <section class='slides'>

<!-- slides/mutexes/10/m.go -->
<article class='title-slide'>
  <div class='title-text'>Introduction to Synchronization</div>
  <div class='subtitle-text'
<p>Demystifying Concurrency</p>
<p>GopherCon Europe 2026</p>
  </div>
  <span class='pagenumber'>1</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Sharing memory</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Goroutines share the program's memory.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>var c int

<span class='codenum'>2</span>func <defn>run</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   var wg sync.WaitGroup
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   wg.Go(count)
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   wg.Go(count)
<span class='codenum'>6</span>   wg.Wait()
<span class='codenum'>7</span>   fmt.Println(c)
<span class='codenum'>8</span>}

<span class='codenum'>9</span>func <defn>count</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>10</span>   for range 20_000 {
<span class='codenum'>11</span>      c++
<span class='codenum'>12</span>   }
<span class='codenum'>13</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div style="height: 10vw"></div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>One possible output:</p>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p> </p>
  </div>
<div></div>
  <div class='output'><pre>
27357
</pre>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p> </p>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>It should be 40000.</p>
  </div>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>2</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Interleavings</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>c++</pre>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>is actually</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>R0 = c
<span class='codenum'>2</span>R0++
<span class='codenum'>3</span>c = R0</pre>
  </div>
  <div style="width: 25vw"></div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>What we want:</p>
<div class="interleave" style="font-size: 70%">
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>G1</th>
<th>G2</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>c++</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>c++</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>What we might get:</p>
<div class="interleave" style="font-size: 70%">
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>G1</th>
<th>G2</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>R0 = c</td>
<td>R0 = c</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>R0++</td>
<td>R0++</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>c = R0</td>
<td>c = R0</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
  </div>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>3</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Using a mutex</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span><span class="em">var mu sync.Mutex</span>

<span class='codenum'>2</span>var c int

<span class='codenum'>3</span>func <defn>run</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   var wg sync.WaitGroup
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   wg.Go(count)
<span class='codenum'>6</span>   wg.Go(count)
<span class='codenum'>7</span>   wg.Wait()
<span class='codenum'>8</span>   fmt.Println(c)
<span class='codenum'>9</span>}

<span class='codenum'>10</span>func <defn>count</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>11</span>   for range 20_000 {
<span class='codenum'>12</span><span class="em">      mu.Lock()</span>
<span class='codenum'>13</span>      c++
<span class='codenum'>14</span><span class="em">      mu.Unlock()</span>
<span class='codenum'>15</span>   }
<span class='codenum'>16</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p> </p>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Only one goroutine between <code>Lock</code> and <code>Unlock</code>
(a <em>critical section</em>).</p>
<p>The code in the critical section happens <em>atomically</em>:
indivisibly.</p>
<p>A mutex limits interleavings.</p>
<p>The zero mutex is unlocked and ready to use.</p>
  </div>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>4</span>
</article>

<!-- slides/mutexes/20/m.go -->
<article>
  <h1>Data races</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>A data race happens when:</p>
<ul>
<li>Two goroutines access the same memory</li>
<li>At least one writes to it</li>
<li>The accesses aren't synchronized</li>
</ul>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p> </p>
  </div>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>same goroutine</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>c++
<span class='codenum'>2</span>fmt.Println(c)</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>different memory</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>wg.Go(func() {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   c1++
<span class='codenum'>3</span>})
<span class='codenum'>4</span>wg.Go(func() {
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   c2++
<span class='codenum'>6</span>})</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>no writes</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>wg.Go(func() {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   fmt.Println(c)
<span class='codenum'>3</span>})
<span class='codenum'>4</span>wg.Go(func() {
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   fmt.Println(c)
<span class='codenum'>6</span>})</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>data race</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code bad'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>wg.Go(func() { c++ })
<span class='codenum'>2</span>wg.Go(func() { c++ })</pre>
  </div>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>5</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>The race detector</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Looks for data races while the program is running.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>var c int

<span class='codenum'>2</span>func <defn>main</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   var wg sync.WaitGroup
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   wg.Go(count)
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   wg.Go(count)
<span class='codenum'>6</span>   wg.Wait()
<span class='codenum'>7</span>   fmt.Println(c)
<span class='codenum'>8</span>}

<span class='codenum'>9</span>func <defn>count</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>10</span>   for range 20_000 {
<span class='codenum'>11</span>      c++
<span class='codenum'>12</span>   }
<span class='codenum'>13</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
<div></div>
  <div class='output'><pre>
27357
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p><code>go run -race .</code></p>
  </div>
<div></div>
  <div class='output'><pre>
==================
WARNING: DATA RACE
Read at 0x000000612e58 by goroutine 7:
main.count()
jba/repos/github.com/jba/concurrency-workshop/slides/mutexes/10/m.go:26 +0x2c
sync.(*WaitGroup).Go.func1()
jba/sdk/go1.25.5/src/sync/waitgroup.go:239 +0x5d

Previous write at 0x000000612e58 by goroutine 8:
main.count()
jba/repos/github.com/jba/concurrency-workshop/slides/mutexes/10/m.go:26 +0x44
sync.(*WaitGroup).Go.func1()
jba/sdk/go1.25.5/src/sync/waitgroup.go:239 +0x5d
</pre>
  </div>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>6</span>
</article>

<!-- slides/mutexes/30/m.go -->
<article>
  <h1>Let&#39;s be clever</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>func <defn>count</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   for range 20_000 {
<span class='codenum'>3</span><span class="em">      x := c + 1</span>
<span class='codenum'>4</span>      mu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>5</span><span class="em">      c = x <comment>// write is protected</span></comment>
<span class='codenum'>6</span>      mu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>7</span>   }
<span class='codenum'>8</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <details>
    <summary>
What do we think about this optimization?</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='answer'>
<p>There is still a data race: a read can happen concurrently with a write.</p>
<div class="interleave" style="font-size: 70%">
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>G1</th>
<th>G2</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>x = c + 1</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>c = x</td>
<td>x = c + 1</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
    </div>
  </details>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>7</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Let&#39;s be even cleverer!</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>func <defn>count</defn>() {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   for range 20_000 {
<span class='codenum'>3</span>      mu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>4</span><span class="em">      x := c <comment>// read is protected</span></comment>
<span class='codenum'>5</span>      mu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>6</span>      x++
<span class='codenum'>7</span>      mu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>8</span><span class="em">      c = x <comment>// write is protected</span></comment>
<span class='codenum'>9</span>      mu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>10</span>   }
<span class='codenum'>11</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <details>
    <summary>
What do we think about this optimization?</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='answer'>
<p>There is no data race, but this code is still incorrect:</p>
<div class="interleave" style="font-size: 70%">
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>G1</th>
<th>G2</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>x = c</td>
<td>x = c</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>x++</td>
<td>x++</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>c = x</td>
<td>c = x</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
    </div>
  </details>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>8</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Data races aren&#39;t the only concurrency bugs</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Data races are about low-level memory access.<br/>
Every data race is a concurrency bug.</p>
<p>But also think about <em>transactions</em>: atomic sequences.<br/>
The read and write must happen atomically.</p>
<p>Examples of transactions:</p>
<ul>
<li>Money transfer</li>
<li>Add/remove an element and update the size</li>
<li>Start fulfilling an order, mark it as in progress</li>
</ul>
  </div>
  <details>
    <summary>
Why doesn't Go make maps concurrency-safe?</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='answer'>
<p>It would be slower, and <em>it wouldn't help in many cases</em>.<br/>
The runtime doesn't know what your transactions are.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <span class='pagenumber'>9</span>
</article>

<!-- slides/mutexes/40/m.go -->
<article>
  <h1>Generating unique IDs, unsafe version</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code bad'><pre>
<comment>// An IDGenerator generates unique identifiers.</comment>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>type <defn>IDGenerator</defn> struct {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   prefix string
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   num    int
<span class='codenum'>4</span>}

<comment>// NewIDGenerator creates an IDGenerator whose</comment>
<comment>// identifiers begin with prefix.</comment>
<span class='codenum'>5</span>func <defn>NewIDGenerator</defn>(prefix string) *IDGenerator {
<span class='codenum'>6</span>   return &amp;IDGenerator{prefix: prefix}
<span class='codenum'>7</span>}

<comment>// NewID generates a unique identifier each time</comment>
<comment>// it is called.</comment>
<span class='codenum'>8</span>func (g *IDGenerator) <defn>NewID</defn>() string {
<span class='codenum'>9</span>   g.num++
<span class='codenum'>10</span>   return fmt.Sprintf(&#34;%s%d&#34;, g.prefix, g.num)
<span class='codenum'>11</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <details>
    <summary>
What can happen if two goroutines call <code>g.NewID()</code> at the same time?</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='answer'>
<p>You might get the same ID twice.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>10</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Generating unique IDs, safe version</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>type <defn>IDGenerator</defn> struct {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   prefix string
<span class='codenum'>3</span><span class="em">   mu     sync.Mutex</span>
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   num    int
<span class='codenum'>5</span>}

<comment>// NewIDGenerator is the same.</comment>

<span class='codenum'>6</span>func (g *IDGenerator) <defn>NewID</defn>() string {
<span class='codenum'>7</span><span class="em">   g.mu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>8</span>   defer g.mu.Unlock()</span>
<span class='codenum'>9</span>   g.num++
<span class='codenum'>10</span>   return fmt.Sprintf(&#34;%s%d&#34;, g.prefix, g.num)
<span class='codenum'>11</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p><code>num</code> must be synchronized to make <code>NewID</code> concurrency-safe</p>
<p><code>prefix</code> is written <em>before</em> all calls to <code>NewID</code></p>
<p>The &quot;mutex hat&quot; convention: declare the mutex field
above the fields it protects</p>
  </div>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>11</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Limit critical section size</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>func (g *IDGenerator) <defn>NewID</defn>() string {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   g.mu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   g.num++
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   g.mu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   return fmt.Sprintf(&#34;%s%d&#34;, g.prefix, g.num)
<span class='codenum'>6</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Keep locked regions (<em>critical sections</em>) small to avoid contention</p>
<p><code>defer</code> is not always needed or useful</p>
  </div>
  <details>
    <summary>
Find and fix the bug.</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>func (g *IDGenerator) <defn>NewID</defn>() string {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   g.mu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   g.num++
<span class='codenum'>4</span><span class="em">   n := g.num</span>
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   g.mu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>6</span>   return fmt.Sprintf(&#34;%s%d&#34;, g.prefix, <span class="em">n</span>)
<span class='codenum'>7</span>}
</pre>
    </div>
    <div class='answer'>
    </div>
  </details>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>12</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Avoid locking during I/O</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>I/O is slow.</p>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Network peers can be <em>arbitrarily</em> slow.</p>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Sometimes you have to copy.</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>func (s *Server) <defn>notifySessions</defn>(n string) {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   s.mu.Lock() <comment>// required to access s.sessions</comment>
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   sessions := slices.Clone(s.sessions)
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   s.pendingNotifications[n] = nil
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   s.mu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>6</span>   <comment>// Do I/O with no locks held.</comment>
<span class='codenum'>7</span>   notifySessions(sessions, n, changeNotificationParams[n], s.opts.Logger)
<span class='codenum'>8</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>From The <a href="https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/go-sdk/blob/4cdbaaf27132e5356ba13973ae50da4edfa876bb/mcp/server.go">Go MCP SDK</a></p>
  </div>
  <span class='pagenumber'>13</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Avoid locking during I/O...unless you need it</h1>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>l.outMu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>2</span>defer l.outMu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>3</span>_, err := l.out.Write(*buf) <comment>// avoid interleaved log lines</comment></pre>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>From The <a href="https://github.com/golang/go/blob/e30e65f7a8bda0351d9def5a6bc91471bddafd3d/src/log/log.go">log package</a></p>
  </div>
  <span class='pagenumber'>14</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Another example of copying</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>We don't know how long the caller will hold on to the iterator.</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<comment>// Sessions returns an iterator that yields a snapshot of the server sessions.</comment>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>func (s *Server) <defn>Sessions</defn>() iter.Seq[*ServerSession] {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   s.mu.Lock()
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   clients := slices.Clone(s.sessions)
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   s.mu.Unlock()
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   return slices.Values(clients)
<span class='codenum'>6</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>From The <a href="https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/go-sdk/blob/4cdbaaf27132e5356ba13973ae50da4edfa876bb/mcp/server.go">Go MCP SDK</a></p>
  </div>
  <span class='pagenumber'>15</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Atomics</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Package <code>sync/atomic</code> exposes CPU atomic operations</p>
<p>&quot;These functions require great care to be used correctly.&quot;</p>
<ul>
<li>Faster than mutexes, but much more dangerous.</li>
<li>Limited operations</li>
<li>Sequences of atomics are <em>not</em> atomic</li>
</ul>
<p>Recommendation: use only for counters</p>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>type <defn>IDGenerator</defn> struct {
<span class='codenum'>2</span>   prefix string
<span class='codenum'>3</span><span class="em">   num    atomic.Int64</span>
<span class='codenum'>4</span>}

<comment>// NewIDGenerator is the same.</comment>

<span class='codenum'>5</span>func (g *IDGenerator) <defn>NewID</defn>() string {
<span class='codenum'>6</span><span class="em">   n := g.num.Add(1)</span>
<span class='codenum'>7</span>   return fmt.Sprintf(&#34;%s%d&#34;, g.prefix, n)
<span class='codenum'>8</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>16</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Mutexes and slices</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Each slice element is a separate memory location.</p>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>No mutex needed here.</p>
  </div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>var wg sync.WaitGroup
<span class='codenum'>2</span>s := make([]int, 2)
<span class='codenum'>3</span>wg.Go(func() { s[0] = 1 })
<span class='codenum'>4</span>wg.Go(func() { s[1] = 2 })
<span class='codenum'>5</span>wg.Wait()</pre>
  </div>
  <span class='pagenumber'>17</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Mutexes and slices, 2</h1>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>var wg sync.WaitGroup
<span class='codenum'>2</span>var s []int
<span class='codenum'>3</span><span class="em">wg.Go(func() { s = append(s, 1) })</span>
<span class='codenum'>4</span><span class="em">wg.Go(func() { s = append(s, 2) })</span>
<span class='codenum'>5</span>wg.Wait()</pre>
  </div>
  <details>
    <summary>
Is a mutex needed here?</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='answer'>
<p>Yes: there is a data race.
Both goroutines write to the same location, <code>s</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <span class='pagenumber'>18</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Mutexes and maps</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code bad'><pre>
<comment>// IDGenerator generates unique IDs with different prefixes.</comment>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>type <defn>IDGenerator</defn> struct {
<span class='codenum'>2</span><span class="em">   nums map[string]int <comment>// prefix to next ID</span></comment>
<span class='codenum'>3</span>}

<span class='codenum'>4</span>func <defn>NewIDGenerator</defn>(prefix string) *IDGenerator {
<span class='codenum'>5</span>   return &amp;IDGenerator{nums: map[string]int{}}
<span class='codenum'>6</span>}

<span class='codenum'>7</span>func (g *IDGenerator) <defn>NewID</defn>(<span class="em">prefix string</span>) string {
<span class='codenum'>8</span>   n := g.nums[prefix]
<span class='codenum'>9</span>   n++
<span class='codenum'>10</span>   g.nums[prefix] = n
<span class='codenum'>11</span>   return fmt.Sprintf(&#34;%s%d&#34;, prefix, n)
<span class='codenum'>12</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Maps need synchronization.</p>
  </div>
  <details>
    <summary>
Why aren't maps like slices?</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='answer'>
<p>The underlying memory locations can change as the map grows and shrinks.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>19</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Mutexes and maps, safely</h1>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>type <defn>IDGenerator</defn> struct {
<span class='codenum'>2</span><span class="em">   mu   sync.Mutex</span>
<span class='codenum'>3</span>   nums map[string]int
<span class='codenum'>4</span>}

<comment>// NewIDGenerator is the same.</comment>

<span class='codenum'>5</span>func (g *IDGenerator) <defn>NewID</defn>(prefix string) string {
<span class='codenum'>6</span><span class="em">   g.mu.Lock()</span>
<span class='codenum'>7</span>   n := g.nums[prefix]
<span class='codenum'>8</span>   n++
<span class='codenum'>9</span>   g.nums[prefix] = n
<span class='codenum'>10</span><span class="em">   g.mu.Unlock()</span>
<span class='codenum'>11</span>   return fmt.Sprintf(&#34;%s%d&#34;, prefix, n)
<span class='codenum'>12</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  <span class='pagenumber'>20</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>Optimizations</h1>
  <div class='text'>
<p>Atomics, as we've seen.</p>
<p><code>sync.RWMutex</code> if there are many more reads than writes.</p>
<p><code>sync.Map</code> if there are very few writes (often just one).</p>
  </div>
  <span class='pagenumber'>21</span>
</article>
<article>
  <h1>sync.Map example</h1>
  <div class="flex"><div>
  <div class='code'><pre>
<span class='codenum'>1</span>type <defn>userTypeInfo</defn> struct{} <comment>// fields omitted</comment>

<span class='codenum'>2</span>var userTypeCache <span class="em">sync.Map</span> <comment>// map[reflect.Type]*userTypeInfo</comment>

<span class='codenum'>3</span>func <defn>validUserType</defn>(rt reflect.Type) (*userTypeInfo, error) {
<span class='codenum'>4</span>   if ui, ok := userTypeCache.Load(rt); ok {
<span class='codenum'>5</span>      return ui.(*userTypeInfo), nil
<span class='codenum'>6</span>   }

<span class='codenum'>7</span>   <comment>// Construct a new userTypeInfo and atomically</comment>
<span class='codenum'>8</span>   <comment>// add it to the userTypeCache.</comment>
<span class='codenum'>9</span>   ut := new(userTypeInfo)
<span class='codenum'>10</span>   <comment>// ...</comment>

<span class='codenum'>11</span>   ui, _ := userTypeCache.LoadOrStore(rt, ut)
<span class='codenum'>12</span>   return ui.(*userTypeInfo), nil
<span class='codenum'>13</span>}
</pre>
  </div>
  </div><div>
  <div class='text'>
<p> </p>
  </div>
  <div class='text'>
<p>From the <a href="https://github.com/golang/go/blob/master/src/encoding/gob/type.go">encoding/gob</a> package.</p>
  </div>
  <details>
    <summary>
What about the race?</p>
    </summary>
    <div class='answer'>
<p>&quot;If we lose the race, we'll waste a little CPU and create a little garbage
but return the existing value anyway.&quot;</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  </div></div> <!-- flex -->
  <span class='pagenumber'>22</span>
</article>
<article>
